<DOC><DOCNO> AP881121-0099 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1240EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Pakistan-Plane 1stLd-Writethru a0514 11-21 0287</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Plane, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0293</SECOND><HEAD>Government Says About 30 Dead in Afghan Plane Downing</HEAD><HEAD>LEADS with 8 grafs with Afghanistan confirming plane downed, 27dead; PICKS up 6th pvs, `Pakistan has ...</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Afghanistan's state-run radio todaysaid all 27 passengers and crew members aboard a Afghan transportplane died when it was shot down by Pakistani forces over theweekend.   A Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman said the plane was flyingseveral miles inside Pakistani airspace when it was attackedSaturday evening near the border town of Parachinar.   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity said it was notclear how many people were aboard the plane.   The Radio Kabul broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said the An-26plane was en route to the eastern city of Jalalabad from the Afghancapital when technical trouble developed.   The pilot put out a call for assistance but was ignored byPakistan authorities, the radio said.   ``Instead of helping pakistan shelled surface-to-air rockets atthe plane against all international laws and norms,'' said the radiobroadcast.   The Pakistani spokesman said: ``The plane was asked to identifyitself and it didn't. It was going deeper into Pakistan's territorywhen it was shot down.''   He did not say how contact had been made with the plane.   Pakistan has repeatedly complained of air violations byneighboring Afghanistan.   The two countries signed a U.N.-mediated agreement in Aprilproviding for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet troopsestimated to be in Afghanistan.   The Kremlin pulled out half of its troops Aug. 15. The remainderare expected to leave by Feb. 15, 1989.   The Soviet Union has been supporting the Marxist Kabul governmentin its fight against U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents.</TEXT></DOC>